\f0\fs28 \cf0 Bankruptcy isn't the only option. Creditors and entrepreneurs can always deal with insolvency on their own. One scenario involves a mutual decision to wind-up business operations. The process and proceeds are identical to those in 
\f1 \cf2 [compulsory liquidation][bankruptcy]
\f0 \cf0 . In another, both parties agree to a workout.\
Like continuation and reorganisation, projects in a workout operate another period; gross earnings are identical to 
\f1 \cf3 $V_2^C$
\f0 \cf0 . Now, however, the original debt 
\f1 \cf3 $D$
\f0 \cf0  due at time 1 is replaced by a new one 
\f1 \cf3 $\\wt D$
\f0 \cf0  due at time 2.\
When negotiating, the entrepreneur's proposal is again take-it-or-leave-it. He offers the smallest 
\f1 \cf3 $\\wt D$
\f0 \cf0  the creditor will accept: one which equates the latter's expected earnings in a workout, 
\f1 \cf3 $\\ol C_1^W$
\f0 \cf0 , with those of his outside option---bankruptcy (
\f1 \cf2 [](#lem2)
\f0 \cf0 ).\
\pard\tx706\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\sa240\pardirnatural

